Peculiarities of doors and windows: L-shaped building with 1 bay depth. Shorter part of the L is 3 bays, longer part of the L is 5 bays.

There is 1 carved door which serves as a main entry. On either side of the doorway are 2 blind windows (on the eastern facade of the ground floor), and 2 square lattice windows (on the first floor). The carved door is on the west-wing ground floor of the shrine. The door is intricately carved with images of wisdom bearers in the lintel end and a Buddha image at the center of the door frame, alongside two other images. The blind windows bear the image of the shrine's deity on the vāhana with other images.
The site has an area with corrugated metal sheets for roofs with square sectioned iron columns in the present-day. These columns define the four bays.
The bay facing south is closed off with a brick wall. All of the other openings have been adapted so they can be closed by means of wooden boards and top-hinged panels.

The second floor features a large five-bayed balcony window which incoorporates six brackets dating from the thirteenth century. It is also flanked by two simple single windows.

In addition, there are two blind windows on the ground floor and two blind windows on the second floor.

A small wooden carved window can be found on the lower floor above the ground floor. Decorative bricks have been used, and the plinth is furnished with delicate ornamental (floral and geometrical) stone carvings.
There is one double leaf lattice door of the main temple with a toraṇa supported by a toraṇathāna. There are no windows, but latticework can be found on all sides of this miniature temple.
This is not a phalcā in the traditional sense. The current building is a poorly built concrete and brick box forming part of a larger modern building.

The main sanctum door is carved, and has a pair of toraṇthāṇ supporting the carved toraṇa. The leaves have lattice openings and the door has a stone threshold. All of the timber elements of the door have been covered in carved metal sheets.
Decorative stone threshold on all four sides but opening on east side only.

1 bhosujhyaḥ on second floor. 5-bay pāsukājhyaḥ on first floor. 2 aedicule windows and 2 lattice windows on first floor. 2 lattice at ground floor. 1 carved door in main shrine building and 2 doors at the side.

The courtyard building's northern and southern wings are both attached to neighboring structures. The west wing has a main entrance gate at its centre and two smaller doors on either side that allow entry from the Patan Darbar Square. The four courtyard elevations feature open arcaded spaces (dalan).
Five opening pasukājhyāḥ on north and south elevation of first floor.
There are four large wooden windows in the back wall facing the hiti. Nine smaller carved windows can be found below the roof.
These windows are "blind windows", i.e. carved frames without openings.
The entry door on the right which leads to the first floor is the original one, while the one to the left leading to the main sanctum is new.
The first and second floor of the monument has a five-bayed pasukājhyāḥ flanked by a smaller gaḥjhyāḥ on each side. The main entrance on the ground floor has a wooden door plated with brass sheets.

The front door of the main sanctum on the ground floor is carved with fine latticed door leaves. The door is flanked by two vertical panels (measuring 155 x 22 cm) that each feature a ghandarva with a human upper body and the hindquarters of a bird. This creature is holding the vase of plenty in both hands alongside a female figure with crossed legs holding a scarf ( see Gutschow 2011, 223).
Struts display carvings of different animals and deities.

The wooden carved windows are reinstalled placing the outer carved face towards the interior sanctum, while the outer position of the windows are represented by the brick masonry blind pattern on west and north side.

The doors and windows have some peculiarities. The main central door is 165cm high, and is decorated with floral patterns on its architraves. The head of the door frame contains three images of Buddha. An image of a deity can be found on either side of the lintel ends. Two small windows with vertical rails flank the main door. The first floor central window is a pasukājhyāḥ with three openings flanked by two small arched openings.
The first floor of the kvāḥpāḥchẽ has a three-bayed pasukājhyāḥ flanked by two smaller carved wooden windows, and its main entrance is flanked by two small latticed windows.
An ivory window can be found on the second floor and corner windows are on the south west corners of the first and second floors. The lattice works are richly carved and are unique to this monument.
The blind windows on the first floor on either side of the central pasukā jhyā are made of concrete. They were installed during the reconstruction of the main building.

The monument has three wooden carved doors on the façade of its ground floor. The central door constitutes the main entrance to the sanctum which is heavily carved in comparision to the other two doors. This central door is also flanked by two small carved windows.

The first floor of the monument has five windows. Three of them are pasukājhyāḥs. The central pasukājhyāḥ is five-bayed whereas the other two are three-bayed. The central five-bayed pasukājhyāḥ is also flanked by two smaller carved windows.
The sides of the windows are solid carved panels.

The single window in the eastern wall is older than the windows in the dwarf storeys, which seem to be replicas of this older window. During the 1993 reconstruction, the columns were made ca. 30 cm higher.

Two historic latticed windows on the ground floor remain. The metal-clad main door and toraṇa above likely date from the mid 19th century. The carved wooden door might be older.

The third floor features one modern window frame. The structure is under construction (March 2019) and temporarily covered with corrugated metal sheets.

The Phalcā has undergone several restorations and alterations and it is not possible to determine the original layout. The south-facing facade retains carved columns, capitals and a cross beam but the openings were filled in with brick. The east-facing side might also have been open as a heavy cross beam indicates. The original roof cover has been lost and was replaced with corrugated metal sheets. Most of the solid stone edging is preserved but modern cement-plastered brick steps were added on the west, north and east.
Shop doors close off the otherwise open phalca.

8 windows (4 in each tier), and 5 aedicules on the ground floor – 2 with iconic carvings and the other 3 with a hole at the center (dyapvaḥ). The main door has a carved outer frame but the original leaves have been lost and so replaced with newer leaves. The entrance has a stone threshold, which is formed of a single piece of stone with lion blocks to support the colonnettes (toraṇathāna).  The door jambs meet the lintels in a mitre joint and the lintel extends on both sides. The carved torana crowns the opening.

The structure can be visually divided into two parts. 1/4 th of the structure is a phalca where as the remaining 3/4ths is a Sattaḥ. The Phalcā has 3 bays facing the front and a single bay to the side.
